> @italobusi , but how do we know that the chassis are under a single stack, which logically behaves as a single switch (for instance)? or we are deciding we are not going to provide that information?

@jccardonar I think you can understand this because theses chassis are under the same network element. This looks like the same as case 1 in https://github.com/ietf-ivy-wg/network-inventory-yang/issues/64#issuecomment-2359312360

IMHO, using the stack component is not needed but also not precluded as show for case 3 in https://github.com/ietf-ivy-wg/network-inventory-yang/issues/64#issuecomment-2359312360. However, my feeling, is that this would be more useful when there is a need to report more than one group of chassis (stacks) within the same network element

issues.body:
The mapping draft has this type:

>   typedef ne-ref {
>     type leafref {
>       path "/nwi:network-inventory/nwi:network-elements"
>          + "/nwi:network-element/nwi:ne-id";
>     }
>     description
>       "This type is used by data models that need to reference
>        Network Element.";
>   }

I suggest we move that type to the base model to ease reuse by other models.

When preparing JSON examples (see PR #76 ), the following when statement failed validation with yanglint:

```
                "derived-from-or-self(../nwi:class,
                'nwi:transceivers-module')";

```

The issue could have been fixed only by updating the component class definition as:

```
            leaf class {
              type identityref {
                base ianahw:hardware-class;
              }
              config false;
              mandatory true;
              description
                "The type of the component.";
            }
```

This issue needs further investigation:
- is it a yanglint implemenation issue or a bug in the current YANG model?
- is there any alternative solution to avoid the use of the union type?

